  <article xml:id="session7wks" label="7821">
    <title>MATH 142 Hands-On, Grades Up</title>
    <introduction>
    <p>
     For workspace between exercises, print this worksheet or download to your device by clicking the printer icon.
    </p>
    </introduction>
<!--START TYPING CONTENT FOR SESSION BELOW HERE-->
<worksheet>
    <title> Session #7 (2.2 - 2.6, 3.1 - 3.3)</title><!-- SECTION 1-->
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &lt; and &amp;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and in the Right Mindset</title>
      <exercise xml:id="warmup-1">
          <introduction>
            <p>Let <m>f(x) = 3x^7 - x^6 + 17</m>.</p>
          </introduction>
          <task xml:id="warmup-1a">
            <statement>
              <p>On what interval(s) is <m>f(x)</m> increasing?</p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="warmup-1b">
            <statement>
              <p>On what interval(s) is <m>f(x)</m> concave down?</p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="warmup-1c">
            <statement>
              <p>On what interval(s) is <m>f(x)</m> both increasing and concave down?</p>
            </statement>
          </task>
        </exercise>
    
    </paragraphs>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let Us Get Our Hands On</title>
      <exercise xml:id="handson-1">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Below is a list of information given about a function <m>f</m>.
              Create sign charts for <m>f'</m> and <m>f''</m> and use the sign
              charts to sketch a graph of the function <m>f</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li><p>Domain of <m>f</m>: <m>(-\infty, -\sqrt{3})\cup (-\sqrt{3}, \sqrt{3}) \cup (\sqrt{3}, \infty)</m></p></li>
                <li><p>Vertical asymptotes at <m>x = \sqrt{3}</m> and <m>x = -\sqrt{3}</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Horizontal asymptote at <m>y = 0</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>f(0) = -\dfrac{1}{3}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f'(0) = 0</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f'(x) \gt 0</m> on <m>(-\infty, -\sqrt{3})</m> and <m>(-\sqrt{3}, 0)</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f'(x) \lt 0</m> on <m>(0,\sqrt{3})</m> and <m>(\sqrt{3}, \infty)</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f''(x) \gt 0</m> on <m>(-\infty, -\sqrt{3})</m> and <m>(\sqrt{3}, \infty)</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f''(x) \lt 0</m> on <m>(-\sqrt{3}, \sqrt{3})</m></p></li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-2">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find <m>f'(x)</m> given <m>f(x) = x^2 + 3x - 1</m> using the
              <em>limit definition of the derivative</em>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-3">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A function <m>p(x)</m> is graphed below. Find all <m>x</m>-values
              where the derivative of <m>p(x)</m> does not exist and give a
              reason for why the derivative does not exist at that <m>x</m>-value.
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-p-graph">
              <caption>Graph of <m>p(x)</m></caption>
              <image source="Graphics/MATH142_HOGU_Session3_Fig6.png" width="60%">
                <description>Graph of p(x) showing points of non-differentiability.</description>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-4">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the derivatives of the following functions. Do not simplify
              your answers; it is okay to just apply the appropriate derivative
              rules and leave the answer unsimplified.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <task xml:id="handson-4a">
            <statement>
              <p><m>\displaystyle f(x)=\left(e^{x+e^x}\right) \sqrt[3]{x^2+1}</m></p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="handson-4b">
            <statement>
              <p><m>\displaystyle f(x)=\frac{x^2}{3^{2x^4+x}}</m></p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="handson-4c">
            <statement>
              <p><m>\displaystyle f(x)=e^{e^{2x}}+\ln \left( \frac{3x^2+2}{5x-1} \right) +e^{\pi}</m></p>
            </statement>
          </task>
          <task xml:id="handson-4d">
            <statement>
              <p><m>\displaystyle f(x)=\left( \log_2(e^{3x}+x^2) \right)^3</m></p>
            </statement>
          </task>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-5">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the equation of the line tangent to
              <m>f(x)=\sqrt{2x^2-2}</m> at <m>x=3</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-6">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given <m>\displaystyle 10x^2 + \frac{13}{2}y^2 - 9 = x^4y^5</m>,
              find <m>\displaystyle \frac{dy}{dx}</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-7">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given the following information about <m>f(x)</m>, determine the
              interval(s) where <m>f(x)</m> is increasing or decreasing and
              concave up or concave down. Identify any <m>x</m>-values where
              <m>f(x)</m> has local extrema and points of inflection (if any).
            </p>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li><p>The domain of <m>f(x)</m> is <m>\displaystyle (-\infty, -4) \cup (-4,\infty)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>\displaystyle f'(x)=\frac{2x^2+16x}{(x+4)^2}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\displaystyle f''(x)=\frac{64}{(x+4)^3}</m></p></li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li><p><m>f</m> is increasing on <fillin characters="20"/></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f</m> is decreasing on <fillin characters="20"/></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f</m> is concave up on <fillin characters="20"/></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f</m> is concave down on <fillin characters="20"/></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f</m> has local extrema at <fillin characters="20"/></p></li>
                <li><p><m>f</m> has point(s) of inflection at <fillin characters="20"/></p></li>
              </ul>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-8">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use the second derivative test to find the relative extrema of
              <m>\displaystyle f(x)=\frac{1}{3}x^3-x^2-8x</m>. Give the
              coordinate points of the extrema.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="handson-9">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A cylindrical tank with a radius of 2 meters is being filled with
              water at a rate of 10 cubic meters per minute. How fast is the
              height of the water increasing when the water is 5 meters deep?
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="fig-cylinder">
              <caption>Cylinder diagram</caption>
              <image source="Graphics/Cylninder.png" width="15%">
                <description>Diagram of a cylinder.</description>
              </image>
            </figure>
            <p>
              <alert>Formulas for Cylinders:</alert>
              Volume: <m>\displaystyle V=\pi r^2h</m>;
              Surface Area: <m>\displaystyle A=2\pi rh+2\pi r^2</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>
  
    </paragraphs>
  
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Now Grades Go Up</title>
      <exercise xml:id="gradesup-1">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A marker manufacturer determined that the total cost, in dollars,
              of producing <m>x</m> boxes of dry erase markers in one day is
              given by <m>C(x)=350+2x-0.01x^2</m>, where <m>0\leq x \leq 150</m>.
              Approximate the cost of producing the 103rd box of dry erase
              markers using marginal analysis.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="gradesup-2">
          <statement>
            <p>
              A marker manufacturer determined that the total cost, in dollars,
              of producing <m>x</m> boxes of dry erase markers in one day is
              given by <m>C(x)=350+2x-0.01x^2</m>, where <m>0\leq x \leq 150</m>.
              Find the <em>exact</em> cost of producing the 103rd box of dry
              erase markers.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="gradesup-3">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given <m>\displaystyle h(x)=\frac{f(x)}{\sqrt{2x}}</m>,
              <m>f(8)=80</m>, and <m>f'(8)=3</m>, find <m>h'(8)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              <ol label="a">
                <li><p><m>\displaystyle -\frac{1}{2}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{2}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\displaystyle \frac{1}{8}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\displaystyle -\frac{77}{4}</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>20</m></p></li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="gradesup-4">
          <statement>
            <p>Circle the graph that fits the criteria below.</p>
            <p>
              <ul>
                <li><p><m>h(-2)=3</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>h'(x) \gt 0</m> on <m>(-\infty,-2)</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>h'(x) \lt 0</m> on <m>(-2,0)</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>h''(x) \lt 0</m> on <m>(-\infty,-1)</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>h'(x)=0</m> at <m>x=-2</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>\lim_{x \to \infty} h''(x) \to \infty</m></p></li>
              </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
              <ol label="a">
                <li>
                  <p>Graph I</p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig-graph1">
                    <caption>Graph I</caption>
                    <image source="Graphics/MATH142_HOGU_Session7_Fig4.png" width="45%">
                      <description>Graph I — candidate graph for h(x).</description>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Graph II</p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig-graph2">
                    <caption>Graph II</caption>
                    <image source="Graphics/MATH142_HOGU_Session7_Fig5.png" width="45%">
                      <description>Graph II — candidate graph for h(x).</description>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Graph III</p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig-graph3">
                    <caption>Graph III</caption>
                    <image source="Graphics/MATH142_HOGU_Session7_Fig8.png" width="45%">
                      <description>Graph III — candidate graph for h(x).</description>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Graph IV</p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig-graph4">
                    <caption>Graph IV</caption>
                    <image source="Graphics/MATH142_HOGU_Session7_Fig6.png" width="45%">
                      <description>Graph IV — candidate graph for h(x).</description>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>Graph V</p>
                  <figure xml:id="fig-graph5">
                    <caption>Graph V</caption>
                    <image source="Graphics/MATH142_HOGU_Session7_Fig7.png" width="45%">
                      <description>Graph V — candidate graph for h(x).</description>
                    </image>
                  </figure>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </exercise>
    </paragraphs>
      

  </worksheet>

